ace-window:
S-tab cycle through subtree display <newline>
org-latex-preview,C-c C-x C-l  <newline>
org-insert-drawer,C-c C-x d  <newline>
to narrow to current subtree,C-x n s<newline>
to widen from current subtree,C-x n w<newline>
to demote a heading,M-right<newline>
to promote a heading,M-left<newline>
to insert new heading at same level,M-RET<newline>
to insert a new to-do at the same level,M-S-RET<newline>
whitespace-end-sentence-delete,C-c d <newline>
to show all content including drawers,C-u C- u C-u <newline>
to move to the next heading,C-c C-n<newline>
to mote to the previous heading,C-c C-p<newline>
to move to the next heading at same level,C-c C-f<newline>
to move to previous heading at same level,C-c C-b<newline>
to move backward to the higher level,C-c C-u<newline>
to execute a code block,C-c C-c<newline>
to edit a code block in a new buffer,C-c '

\begin{enumerate}
\item Place the TextCursor at the beginning of the first line.
\item `C-x (’ to start recording a keyboard macro.
\item ‘C-e’ (or ‘M-x end-of-line’) to move the cursor to the end of the line.
\item Type “-- foobar was here”
\item ‘C-f’ (or ‘M-x forward-char’) to move the cursor to the beginning of the next line. (C-n might not go to the next line if the macro encounters a long line long that wraps on the screen)
\item `C-x )’ to stop recording the keyboard macro.
\item ‘C-u 0 C-x e’ to execute the macro an infinite number of times until the end of the file is reached (See InfiniteArgument).
\end{enumerate}
